2 Introduction: Notation
Throughout this course, we will study {} of biological systems and as such we will consider \(x \in \mathbb R^n\), \(t \in [0, \infty)\) and functions \(c: \mathbb R^n \times [0, \infty) \to \mathbb R\), where \(n=1,2,3\). For example:

\(c(t,x)\) - the density of a population [number per volume] at time \(t\) and position \(x\) (at \((t,x)\))
\(c(t,x)\) - the concentration of a substance (chemicals, particles) [mass per volume] at time \(t\) and position \(x\) (at \((t,x)\))
\(c(t,x)\) - the temperature at \((t,x)\).

##Derivation of conservation equations}
A conservation equation is the most fundamental statement through which changes in the distribution of the density (or concentration, temperature) is described. \[
\begin{pmatrix}
\text{rate of change}\\
\text{ in the population density}
\end{pmatrix}
= \begin{pmatrix}
\text{spatial movement}
\end{pmatrix}
+
\begin{pmatrix}
\text{birth, growth, death},\\
\text{production or degradation}\\
  \text{due to chemical reactions}
\end{pmatrix}
\]
In this introductory first section, we shall neglect spatial movement and consider examples of growth/death and chemical reactions. Spatial movement will be considered in the next section and subsequently throughout the course.

2.0.1 Modelling the growth of bacteria in a petri dish (flask) containing nutrient medium}
Bacteria are found to reproduce by undergoing successive cell divisions.
Denote by \(N(t)\) - bacterial density observed at time \(t\) [number of cells per volume].
Over a period of one unit time a single bacterial cell divides, then its daughter cells divide, and so forth, leading to a total of \(K\) new bacterial cells.
Define \(K\) - rate of reproduction per unit time, \(K&gt;0\), and
\[\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq:N_1}
\begin{aligned}
N(t+\Delta t) &=  \quad N(t)  & + \quad  &K N(t) \Delta t \\
\text{ density at time } t + \Delta t & \quad   \text{ density at time } t  & &\text{ increase in density due to}\\
&& &\text{reproduction during}\\
&& &\text{ the time interval } \Delta t
\end{aligned}
\end{eqnarray}\] Assuming that \(N\) is differentiable, dividing equation \(\eqref{eq:N_1}\) by \(\Delta t\) and tailing limit as \(\Delta t \to 0\) imply \[\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq:N_2}
\frac{dN}{dt} = K N
\end{eqnarray}\] The growth rate \(K\) can take several forms e.g. 
We denote by \(\alpha\) the units of nutrients consumed during the production of one unit of population increment (Note: the quantity \(Y= 1/\alpha\) is called the yield) and obtain \[\begin{eqnarray}
& \frac{dN}{dt} = K(c) N = \kappa \, c \, N,  & \quad N(0) = N_0\label{eq:N_3}\\
& \frac{ dc}{dt} = - \alpha \frac{dN}{dt} = - \alpha   \kappa \, c \, N,  &\quad  c(0)= c_0\label{eq:C_1}
\end{eqnarray}\]
We can determine the nutrient concentration by solving equation \(\eqref{eq:C_1}\). We can integrate \(\eqref{eq:C_1}\) with respect to time and obtain \[\begin{equation}\label{sol_c}
c(t)  = - \alpha N(t) + c(0)+ \alpha N(0) = - \alpha N(t) + \beta,
\end{equation}\] where \(\beta=c_0 +\alpha N_0\). Using \(\eqref{sol_c}\) in \(\eqref{eq:N_3}\) we obtain an equation just for \(N\) \[\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq:N_4}
\frac{dN}{dt} = \kappa ( \beta- \alpha N)  N, \qquad  N(0)= N_0\quad  \text{ logistic equation (logistic growth)}
\end{eqnarray}\] Here we have \(K=K(N) = \kappa (\beta - \alpha N)\).
The last equation can be rewritten as
\[\begin{eqnarray}\label{eq:N_5}
\frac{dN}{dt} = \rho  N \,  (1 - \frac N B)  \qquad \quad N(0)= N_0,
\end{eqnarray}\] where \(\rho = \kappa \beta\) is the {} and \(B = \frac \beta \alpha\) is the {}. The solution of \(\eqref{eq:N_5}\) is given by \[
N(t)= \frac{ N_0 K} { N_0 + (B-N_0) e^{-\rho t}} \; .
\]
 Additional to growth we may assume that cells die at rate \(d\) and the simple growth equation \(\eqref{eq:N_2}\) can be generalised to \[
\frac{dN}{dt} = KN - d N ,
\] where \(d\) is the mortality (death) rate.
 The fact that individuals compete for food, habitat (i.e. space) or any limited resources, means that an increase in the net mortality of the population may be observed under crowded conditions \[
\frac{dN}{dt} = KN - d_1 N^2 ,
\] where \(d=d_1N\) is the mortality (death) rate and is proportional to the population density.


2.0.2 Chemical reactions}

Most biochemical reactions involve proteins called {} which act as catalysts of chemical reactions. Enzymes react selectively on specific compounds called {}.
A substrate \(S\) reacts, in a {}, with an enzyme \(E\) to form a {} \(SE\) or \(C\), which in turn is converted into a product \(P\). This may be described as follows:
\[\begin{eqnarray}
S + E &\reaction{k_{-1}}{k_1}& C \;\;\;\;\; {\rm (reversible)} \nonumber \\
C & \stackrel{k_2}{\rightarrow} & P + E \nonumber
\end{eqnarray}\]
where \(k_{-1}, k_1\) and \(k_2\) are rate constants (\(&gt;0\)) determining the rate of the reaction i.e. how fast the reaction proceeds. %\begin{eqnarray} %S+ E %^{k_1}{k{-1} }SE P + E, %\end{eqnarray}
%\(\longrightleftharpoons\) - reaction is reversible
The law of mass action states that the rate of a reaction is proportional to the product of the concentrations of the reactants. (Note: The law of mass action is only an approximation, but it is a very good one for dilute solutions of the chemical concerned.)
We denote the concentrations $ [ ; ]$ as follows: \[
s=[S], \quad e=[E], \quad c = [SE], \quad p =[P]
\] and obtain \[\begin{eqnarray}
\begin{aligned}
\frac{ds}{dt}& = - k_1 es + k_{-1} c, \qquad && s(0) = s_0,  \label{eq:s}\\
\frac{de}{dt} &= - k_1 es + k_{-1} c + k_2 c, \qquad && e(0) = e_0, \label{eq:e} \\
\frac{dc}{dt} &=  k_1 es - k_{-1} c - k_2 c, \qquad && c(0) = 0, \label{eq:c} \\
\frac{dp}{dt} &=  k_{2} c, \qquad && p(0) = p_0. \label{eq:p}
\end{aligned}
\end{eqnarray}\]
A study of this system is given in Homework 1.
